#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <sstream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    string line;
    // Read T
    getline(cin, line);
    int T;
    {
        stringstream ss(line);
        ss >> T;
    }

    // Read blank line after T (if any)
    // Actually there may be a blank line right after T
    // But we handle this by reading the next non-empty line

    for (int t = 0; t < T; ++t) {
        // Read blank line before test case (except possibly first)
        // We'll just read until we get a non-empty line for W
        int W;
        while (true) {
            if (!getline(cin, line)) break;
            if (line.empty()) continue;
            stringstream ss(line);
            ss >> W;
            break;
        }

        bool possible = true;
        int prev_left = -1000; // some sentinel
        int prev_right = -1000; // some sentinel

        for (int i = 0; i < W; ++i) {
            getline(cin, line);
            int y1, y2;
            stringstream ss(line);
            ss >> y1 >> y2;

            // y1 = top of canyon (bottom landmass top edge)
            // y2 = bottom of canyon (top landmass bottom edge)
            // The gap at this column is from y1 (bottom landmass top) to y2 (top landmass bottom)
            // For a perfect fit, after shifting columns together (left/right), 
            // the gap profile must be "flat" - i.e., all columns have the same gap height
            // and the gap height must be such that top and bottom meet.
            // Actually, we're pushing from left and right to squeeze the gap shut.
            // The land is like: bottom piece has a top surface, top piece has a bottom surface.
            // We can shift horizontally (push together) which means columns can move relative to each other?
            // Wait, re-reading: "2 талаас шахаж нийлүүлэх" - pushing from two sides.
            // The land is split horizontally (top and bottom). We push from left and right.
            // Actually "газар хөндлөгөөрөө хагарсан" means split horizontally (across), 
            // so top and bottom parts. Then we push from the sides (left and right) to squeeze them together.
            // This means the columns can be compressed horizontally.
            // Each column has a gap: from y1 (top of bottom piece) to y2 (bottom of top piece).
            // When we push from sides, the columns get squeezed, meaning the gap shapes must match 
            // so that when pushed together, they interlock perfectly with no gaps.
            // 
            // Let's think differently: We have W columns. At column i, the bottom piece has height y1_i 
            // (its top surface y-coordinate) and top piece has bottom surface at y2_i.
            // The gap (canyon) between them at column i is from y1_i to y2_i.
            // We are pushing the left and right sides together (compressing horizontally).
            // This is like: we can choose a horizontal offset to slide the two pieces
            // so that the top piece's bottom surface fits into the bottom piece's top surface.
            //
            // Actually, re-reading more carefully: "Газрыг х, у тэнхлэгт байгаа гэж үзэх ба газар хөндлөгөөрөө хагарсан.
            // Өөрөөр хэлбэл хагарлын үр дүнд газар дээр доор гэсэн 2 эх газарт хуваагдсан."
            // So the land was split horizontally - into top and bottom parts.
            // "2 талаас шахаж нийлүүлэх" - push from 2 sides to merge them.
            // The "2 sides" likely mean the left and right sides of the city.
            // So we push from left and right to close the gap.
            // 
            // I think the problem is: given the profile of the canyon (gap between top and bottom land),
            // can we compress it horizontally (push columns together) so that the gap closes entirely?
            // This is equivalent to: can we remove some columns or squash them so that the y1 and y2 
            // surfaces match perfectly?
            //
            // Let's look at the sample:
            // W=5
            // 2 1
            // 0 -1
            // 1 0
            // 1 0
            // 2 1
            // Output: yes
            //
            // Plot: column 1: y1=2, y2=1  -> gap from 2 down to 1? That doesn't make sense if y1 > y2.
            // Wait, y1 is "хавцлын хамгийн дээд талын мөрийг" = topmost row of canyon,
            // y2 is "хавцлын хамгийн доод талын мөрийг" = bottommost row of canyon.
            // Canyon is the gap between the two landmasses.
            // So y1 is the top of the gap (bottom of upper landmass? no...)
            // Actually re-read: "эхний тоо y1 нь хавцлын хамгийн дээд талын мөрийг, дараагийн тоо y2 нь хавцлын хамгийн доод талын мөрийг"
            // So y1 is top of canyon, y2 is bottom of canyon.
            // The canyon is between the two landmasses. So top of canyon = bottom of upper landmass? 
            // And bottom of canyon = top of lower landmass?
            //
            // Wait: "Газар дээр доор гэсэн 2 эх газарт хуваагдсан" - the land split into upper and lower land.
            // Between them is the canyon/gap. 
            // y1 = хавцлын хамгийн дээд талын мөр = topmost row of canyon = bottom edge of upper landmass
            // y2 = хавцлын хамгийн доод талын мөр = bottommost row of canyon = top edge of lower landmass
            //
            // But in the sample:
            // 2 1 -> top of canyon = 2, bottom of canyon = 1. So canyon spans y=1 to y=2? But y1 > y2.
            // If y1 is top and y2 is bottom, we'd expect y1 >= y2 typically (higher y is upward).
            // Here y1=2, y2=1, so top of canyon is at y=2, bottom is at y=1. The canyon height = 1.
            // 0 -1 -> top=0, bottom=-1. Canyon from -1 to 0.
            // 1 0 -> top=1, bottom=0.
            // 1 0 -> same
            // 2 1 -> top=2, bottom=1.
            //
            // So the canyon profile is:
            // Col 0: top=2, bottom=1  (gap at y=1..2)
            // Col 1: top=0, bottom=-1 (gap at y=-1..0)
            // Col 2: top=1, bottom=0  (gap at y=0..1)
            // Col 3: top=1, bottom=0  (same)
            // Col 4: top=2, bottom=1  (same as col 0)
            //
            // Now we push from left and right to close the gap. 
            // "2 талаас шахаж нийлүүлэх" - I think it means we can shift the two landmasses 
            // (upper and lower) relative to each other horizontally to see if they fit.
            // Like, we can slide the top piece left/right over the bottom piece and see if 
            // they can interlock perfectly (the canyon disappears).
            //
            // Actually, maybe it's simpler: We have two pieces (top and bottom) that were split.
            // The top piece has a bottom surface defined by y2 at each column.
            // The bottom piece has a top surface defined by y1 at each column.
            // We can slide the top piece horizontally relative to the bottom piece.
            // After sliding by some offset d, the top piece's column i aligns with bottom piece's column i+d.
            // They fit perfectly if for all aligned columns, the surfaces match (y1_bottom[i] == y2_top[i+d] or something).
            // Or rather they fit if there's no gap: the surfaces touch everywhere.
            // But the canyon is the space between them. If we shift, the gap at column i becomes 
            // something like y1[i] (bottom piece top) and y2[i+d] (top piece bottom).
            // For no gap, we need y1[i] >= y2[i+d]? No, the surfaces need to meet.
            //
            // Wait: y1 is the top of the bottom piece (its upper surface). y2 is the bottom of the top piece (its lower surface).
            // The canyon at column i is between y1[i] (the top of the bottom) and y2[i] (the bottom of the top).
            // If y1[i] >= y2[i], then there's no gap (they overlap or touch).
            // If y1[i] < y2[i], there's a gap (canyon).
            // 
            // When we push from the sides, we compress the land horizontally. This would mean 
            // we can remove some columns or adjust positions so that the surfaces align.
            //
            // Let me think about it differently. The sample says "yes". Let me check if simply 
            // checking whether the sequence of y1 and y2 are such that... hmm.
            //
            // Actually, I think the problem is about "can we shift the left side and right side 
            // (i.e., compress horizontally) so that the gap closes?" 
            // This is essentially: can we rearrange/match the columns so that y1 and y2 pairs 
            // satisfy y1 >= y2 (no gap) everywhere?
            //
            // But "2 талаас шахаж нийлүүлэх" might mean pushing from the left and right edges 
            // of the entire city. So we push the left part to the right and right part to the left.
            // This would fold/compress the land.
            //
            // Let's search my memory: This problem is from SPOJ RGB7278 "Хавцал" (Canyon).
            // I think this is a known problem where you have two profiles (upper and lower) 
            // and you need to check if they can be made to match by shifting horizontally.
            // The answer is "yes" if the sequence of (y2_i - y1_i) is the same when read 
            // from both ends? Or if there's some symmetry?
            //
            // Let's analyze the sample:
            // Differences (y2 - y1): 
            // Col 0: 1 - 2 = -1
            // Col 1: -1 - 0 = -1
            // Col 2: 0 - 1 = -1
            // Col 3: 0 - 1 = -1
            // Col 4: 1 - 2 = -1
            // All differences are -1, so the gap size is 1 everywhere. 
            // And the shape is symmetric: 2,1 -> 0,-1 -> 1,0 -> 1,0 -> 2,1
            //
            // Hmm, actually maybe the condition is simpler: 
            // If the top piece's bottom profile (y2 values) and bottom piece's top profile (y1 values)
            // are such that the gap width is constant across all columns AND the profiles are mirror images?
            //
            // Let me think about: "2 талаас шахаж нийлүүлэх" = pushing from 2 sides to merge.
            // If you have a canyon profile (a sequence of gaps), you push from left and right 
            // to close the canyon. This is like: the left wall moves right, the right wall moves left.
            // The question is whether the two sides can meet without any gap remaining.
            //
            // Wait, maybe it's about the two sides of the canyon (the left edge and right edge of the split).
            // The land split vertically down the middle? "газар хөндлөгөөрөө хагарсан" means split 
            // horizontally (across). So the split is horizontal = top and bottom. 
            // But then "2 талаас шахаж нийлүүлэх" - push from 2 sides. 
            // The 2 sides could be the top and bottom pieces? 
            // Or the 2 sides of the city (left and right)?
            //
            // Given the input format: each column gives y1 (top of canyon) and y2 (bottom of canyon).
            // If we think of it as: the canyon runs horizontally across the city. For each vertical 
            // column (x position), the canyon has a top edge (y1) and bottom edge (y2).
            // To close the canyon, we need to push the top piece down and bottom piece up 
            // so they meet. But "2 талаас" = from 2 sides... if the split is horizontal,
            // the sides are top and bottom. So we push the top piece down and bottom piece up.
            //
            // But the input gives for each column the top of canyon (y1) and bottom of canyon (y2).
            // If we push top piece down and bottom piece up, the gap at each column reduces.
            // For the gap to close everywhere simultaneously, all columns need to have the same 
            // gap height (y2 - y1)? Or maybe the shapes need to be compatible such that when 
            // pushed vertically, they interlock?
            //
            // Hmm, let me reconsider. I think "2 талаас шахаж нийлүүлэх" means pushing the 
            // two *horizontal* sides (left and right walls of the canyon) together. 
            // That is, the canyon has a left wall and a right wall (like a fissure). 
            // We push those walls together horizontally.
            //
            // But the input gives y1 (top) and y2 (bottom) for each column. How does that relate 
            // to left/right walls?
            //
            // OK let me look at this from a different angle. There's a SPOJ problem "CANYON" or similar.
            // The sample yields "yes" for the given input.
            //
            // Let me try to think about what "yes" means:
            // W=5 columns
            // (2,1), (0,-1), (1,0), (1,0), (2,1)
            //
            // If I look at y1 sequence: [2, 0, 1, 1, 2]
            // If I look at y2 sequence: [1, -1, 0, 0, 1]
            // y1 is the top of canyon, y2 is the bottom of canyon.
            //
            // Maybe the problem is: We have two pieces of land (upper and lower) that were 
            // separated by the earthquake. The upper piece's bottom surface is defined by y2 at each column.
            // The lower piece's top surface is defined by y1 at each column.
            // We can slide the upper piece horizontally relative to the lower piece.
            // If they can fit together (the surfaces match up) with no gaps, answer is yes.
            //
            // For no gaps, we need: at every column where they align after shifting, 
            // y1[i] should be >= y2[i+d] (the bottom piece's top is at or above the top piece's bottom).
            // Actually it should be y1[i] == y2[i+d] for them to fit perfectly (touching).
            //
            // With the sample:
            // y1 = [2, 0, 1, 1, 2]
            // y2 = [1, -1, 0, 0, 1]
            // If we shift by d=0: compare (2,1), (0,-1), (1,0), (1,0), (2,1) -> y1 > y2 everywhere, so they'd overlap.
            // But that means the pieces intersect/overlap, not fit perfectly.
            //
            // Hmm.
            //
            // Let me try another interpretation: The "2 талаас" are left and right. So we push 
            // from left and right ends of the city towards the center. The city compresses 
            // horizontally. As it compresses, the gap (canyon) at each column changes.
            // The question is whether there exists some compression amount such that the gap 
            // closes completely (no empty space between top and bottom).
            //
            // But this is getting complex for a problem aimed at 7th-8th graders.
            //
            // Let me try the simplest possible interpretation: The two pieces (top and bottom) 
            // just need to be mirror images of each other, because when you push them together 
            // horizontally, they interlock like puzzle pieces.
            //
            // Actually, re-reading: "2 талаас шахаж нийлүүлэх" could mean we push the two 
            // pieces towards each other from the sides. The pieces are: the upper landmass 
            // and the lower landmass. We push them horizontally (left-right) so they slide 
            // past each other? No, that doesn't make sense.
            //
            // Let me think about what makes the sample "yes" and what would be "no".
            // Maybe the answer is "yes" if the sequence of y1 values equals the reverse 
            // of the sequence of y2 values, or something like that?
            //
            // y1 = [2, 0, 1, 1, 2]
            // y2 = [1, -1, 0, 0, 1]
            // Reverse of y2 = [1, 0, 0, -1, 1]
            // Not equal to y1.
            //
            // What if we look at (y1 - y2) or (y2 - y1)?
            // diff = y1 - y2 = [1, 1, 1, 1, 1] - all 1! That's interesting.
            // So the canyon height (y1 - y2) is constant = 1.
            //
            // If the canyon height is constant, does that guarantee "yes"?
            // Let's think: if y1 - y2 = h (constant) for all columns, then the gap has 
            // uniform height h. You can push the top piece down by h and they'll touch perfectly.
            // But if the heights vary, you can't close the gap uniformly.
            //
            // But wait, the problem says we push from sides (2 талаас), not top-bottom.
            // "2 талаас шахаж нийлүүлэх" - push from two sides to merge.
            // The two sides could be... the two landmasses (top and bottom)?
            // 
            // Actually in Mongolian, "талаас" can mean "from the side/part". 
            // "2 талаас шахаж нийлүүлэх" = push from the two parts/sides to merge them.
            // Given there are two landmasses (upper and lower), it means push the upper 
            // and lower parts together. That's vertical compression.
            //
            // And for vertical compression to close the canyon completely, you need the 
            // canyon height (y1 - y2) to be the same at every column. Because if you push 
            // them together by distance d, all gaps reduce by d. To close all gaps, 
            // all gaps must have the same initial height.
            //
            // So condition: all columns have the same gap height (y1 - y2 = constant).
            //
            // Let's verify with the sample: y1 - y2 = 2-1=1, 0-(-1)=1, 1-0=1, 1-0=1, 2-1=1. Yes.
            //
            // Let's think of a "no" case: If the heights differ, you can't close all gaps 
            // by a uniform vertical push.
            //
            // So the solution is: for each test case, check if (y1 - y2) is the same for all columns.
            // Output "yes" if so, "no" otherwise.
            //
            // This is simple enough for 7th-8th graders!
            //
            // Let me double-check by re-reading the problem statement in Mongolian.
            // "Газар хөндлөгөөрөө хагарсан" - the land split horizontally (across).
            // So top and bottom parts.
            // "2 талаас шахаж нийлүүлэх" - push from 2 sides/parts to merge.
            // Makes sense as vertical push.
            //
            // And y1 is "хавцлын хамгийн дээд талын мөр" = topmost row of the canyon = bottom of upper part.
            // y2 is "хавцлын хамгийн доод талын мөр" = bottommost row of the canyon = top of lower part.
            // So the gap (canyon) goes from y2 (bottom) to y1 (top). Height = y1 - y2.
            // For uniform vertical compression to close it, all heights must be equal.

            int height = y1 - y2;
            if (i == 0) {
                prev_left = height;
                prev_right = height;
            } else {
                if (height != prev_left) {
                    possible = false;
                }
            }
        }

        if (t > 0) {
            cout << '\n';
        }
        cout << (possible ? "yes" : "no") << '\n';
    }

    return 0;
}
